{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"8a5227e8-5b07-45cc-8d9a-6b3539890bae","content":"```bash\ndotnet test --filter \"FullyQualifiedName~SmsNotificationTests\"\n```\n\nThis uses the `~` (contains) operator to match any test whose fully qualified name includes `SmsNotificationTests`, which will run both `SendSms_HealthCheck` and `SendSms_ValidPhone_Succeeds`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"260891b8-2826-44b4-a4e8-d63ca577a4c3","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"This is a TUnit project. TUnit uses its own test adapter. To filter by class name, the user needs to use the `--filter` option with `dotnet test`.\n\nFor TUnit, the filter syntax uses `FullyQualifiedName` or `ClassName`. The standard dotnet test filter for class name would be:\n\n```\ndotnet test --filter \"ClassName=SmsNotificationTests\"\n```\n\nor using FullyQualifiedName:\n\n```\ndotnet test --filter \"FullyQualifiedName~SmsNotificationTests\"\n```\n\nTUnit integrates with the standard dotnet test infrastructure, so the standard filter expressions should work.","outputTokens":246,"requestId":"481B:286B29:84A535:98D10F:69FBEAAC"},"id":"e0ee1ca8-e4c7-471a-af28-c97ed9bcb569","timestamp":"2026-05-07T01:28:20.108Z","parentId":"d1a7d2c2-a990-4b33-9320-1a0fdd3e2ebe"}
